    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-10-30T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-10-30T12:00:00-05:00" n="750"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d750">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00113 European War 1939/10–3044:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The American Representative on the Advisory Council for
                        Italy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-10-30T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 30, 1944—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 31—9:19 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>624. A note dated October 28 just received from Italian Prime Minister<note
                        n="79" xml:id="d750fn79">Ivanoe Bonomi.</note> states that the competent
                    Italian authorities have taken steps for promoting the desequestration of
                    property of British and American subjects in Italy to point out to my Government
                    that the Government of Italy expects similar measures to be taken in the United
                    States with regard to Italian property still under sequestration. He requests
                    any assurance which I can give him in the matter.</p>
                <p>In this general connection the Italian Government was apprised by me some months
                    ago of the basis of treatment accorded to Italian property in the United States
                    insofar as was set forth in Department’s instruction No. 3 of May 25, 1944.<note
                        n="80" xml:id="d750fn80">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>I should appreciate being informed as to what I should now say to President
                    Bonomi in reply to his note.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
